<HEADLINE>
<P>
AT LEAST THE PRICES ARE FIT FOR A KING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As a season-ticket holder for the Los Angeles Kings, I begin preparing myself 
for yet another ticket price increase in April, just about the time the Kings 
are eliminated from the playoffs. And every year, no matter how well I prepare 
myself, I get the shock of my life when the bill arrives. 
</P>
<P>
This year was no exception. 
</P>
<P>
When I first bought my season seats in 1986, I paid $1,659 (parking included) 
for a pair in the loge. This year, those same seats will cost me $4,032, an 
increase of 243% for a team that has never been remotely close to winning a 
Stanley Cup in a town that is hardly a haven for hockey. 
</P>
<P>
I just wonder what Bruce McNall's response will be when Wayne Gretzky is gone, 
the Kings continue to flounder in fourth place and still have not come close to 
winning a Stanley Cup, the Johnny-come-lately fan no longer buys tickets and 
the longtime fan can't afford it. What will you do then, Bruce? 
</P>
<P>
MICHELLE BUEHLER 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
