<TEXT>
<P>
The government of Israel will pay $20,000 to each of the families of seven 
Palestinians killed May 20 by an Israeli impersonating a soldier, a Defense 
Ministry spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that Israel is not obligated to make the payments but is 
offering the money because of the "unique circumstances" of the killings. The 
gunman shot down the seven, from the occupied Gaza Strip, while they waited for 
work as day laborers in the town of Rishon le Zion near Tel Aviv. The killings 
inflamed tensions throughout the occupied lands and touched off a wave of 
rioting. 
